SIMPLE: mace
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mace
<hw>Mace</hw> <pr>(m⟦amac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Jav. & Malay.
<ets>m⟦amac⟧s</ets>, fr. Skr. <ets>m⟦amac⟧sha</ets> a bean.]</ety>
<def>A money of account in China equal to one tenth of a tael; also, a
weight of 57.98 grains.</def> <rj><au>S. W. Williams.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mace</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mace
<hw>Mace</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>macis</ets>, L.
<ets>macis</ets>, <ets>macir</ets>, Gr. <?/; cf. Skr.
<ets>makar</ets>anda the nectar or honey of a flower, a fragrant
mango.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of spice; the aril which
partly covers nutmegs. See <er>Nutmeg</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <stype>Red mace</stype> is the aril of <spn>Myristica
tingens</spn>, and <stype>white mace</stype> that of <spn>Myristica
Otoba</spn>, -- East Indian trees of the same genus with the nutmeg
tree.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mace</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mace
<hw>Mace</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mace</ets>, F.
<ets>masse</ets>, from (assumed) L. <ets>matea</ets>, of which the dim.
<ets>mateola</ets> a kind of mallet or beetle, is found.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A heavy staff or club of metal; a spiked club; -- used
as weapon in war before the general use of firearms, especially in the
Middle Ages, for breaking metal armor.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death with his <qex>mace</qex> petrific . . . smote.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A staff borne by, or carried
before, a magistrate as an ensign of his authority.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Swayed
the royal <xex>mace</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An officer who carries a mace as an emblem of
authority; a macebearer.</def> <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A knobbed mallet used by curriers in dressing
leather to make it supple.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Billiards)</fld> <def>A rod for playing billiards,
having one end suited to resting on the table and pushed with one
hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mace</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mace
<hw>Mace</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Trademark.]</ety>
<def>A chemical preparation containing tear gas in a solvent, packaged
in the form of a spray, and used to temporarily incapacitate people,
such as rioters or criminals, by causing intense eye and skin
irritation; also called <altname>chemical mace</altname>. It is designed
to be a non-lethal weapon for defending against violent
people.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mace bearer</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>macebearer</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>
